an try using the square root of the item multiplied by the standard deviation of bins and then add the cosine of the mean of bins.\n\nFunction 1:\nreturn np.sqrt(item) * np.std(bins) + np.cos(np.mean(bins))\n\n2. Next, perhaps using the cube of the item and multiplying it with the maximum bin value, then adding the logarithm of the item.\n\nFunction 2:\nreturn (item ** 3) * np.max(bins) + np.log(item)\n\n3. Let me try using the item divided by the mean of bins, then take the exponential of that, and multiply by the standard deviation.\n\nFunction 3:\nreturn np.exp(item / np.mean(bins)) * np.std(bins)\n\n4. How about using the item multiplied by the variance of bins and adding the sine of the maximum bin.\n\nFunction 4:\nreturn item * np.var(bins) + np.sin(np.max(bins))\n\n5. Maybe the item squared multiplied by the mean of bins, and then subtract the square root of the mean.\n\nFunction 5:\nreturn (item ** 2) * np.mean(bins) - np.sqrt(np.mean(bins))\n\n6. Let's use the item multiplied by the sum of the bins, then add the cosine of the item.\n\nWait, but sum is not in the allowed operations. Oh, allowed operations include array manipulations like np.sum. So, yes.\n\nFunction 6:\nreturn item * np.sum(bins) + np.cos(item)\n\n7. Another idea: take the item, subtract the minimum bin, then multiply by the exponential of the mean.\n\nFunction 7:\nreturn (item - np.min(bins)) * np.exp(np.mean(bins))\n\n8. How about using the item multiplied by the maximum bin, then subtract the logarithm of the mean.\n\nFunction 8:\nreturn item * np.max(bins) - np.log(np.mean(bins))\n\n9. Let's try using the square of the item multiplied by the standard deviation, then add the tangent of the mean.\n\nFunction 9:\nreturn (item ** 2) * np.std(bins) + np.tanh(np.mean(bins))\n\n10. Lastly, maybe using the item multiplied by the difference between max and min bins, then add the square of the mean.\n\nFunction 10:\nreturn item * (np.max(bins) - np.min(bins)) + (np.mean(bins)) ** 2\n\nWait, let me check each function to ensure they are unique and meet the requirements.\n\nFunction 1: Uses sqrt, std, cos.\nFunction 2: Cube, max, log.\nFunction 3: Exp, std, mean division.\nFunction 4: Var, sin, max.\nFunction 5: Square, mean multiplication, sqrt subtraction.\nFunction 6: Sum, item multiplication, cos.\nFunction 7: Min subtraction, exp mean.\nFunction 8: Max multiplication, log mean subtraction.\nFunction 9: Square, std, tanh.\nFunction 10: Max-min difference, mean square.\n\nEach seems unique in their operation combinations. Now, let me write them as functions.\n</think>\n\nHere are 10 unique implementations of the `priority` function, each using distinct combinations of allowed operations:\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sqrt(item) * np.std(bins) + np.cos(np.mean(bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item ** 3) * np.max(bins) + np.log(item)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item / np.mean(bins)) * np.std(bins)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return item * np.var(bins) + np.sin(np.max(bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item ** 2) * np.mean(bins) - np.sqrt(np.mean(bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return item * np.sum(bins) + np.cos(item)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item - np.min(bins)) * np.exp(np.mean(bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return item * np.max(bins) - np.log(np.mean(bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item ** 2) * np.std(bins) + np.tanh(np.mean(bins))\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return item * (np.max(bins) - np.min(bins)) + (np.mean(bins)) ** 2\n", 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    re