t\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    can_fit = bins >= item\n    remaining = bins - item\n    priority = np.where(can_fit, -remaining, -np.inf)\n    return priority\n\nHeuristic 3: First Fit\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    can_fit = bins >= item\n    priority = np.zeros_like(bins)\n    priority[can_fit] = 1\n    # To make the first occurrence have higher priority, but in vectorized form, it's tricky.\n    # Alternatively, set all can_fit to 1, others to 0.\n    # But how to make the first bin have higher priority? Maybe multiply by their index.\n    # But since it's vectorized, perhaps the first bin is the one with the smallest index.\n    # So, the priority is 1 for can_fit, and 0 otherwise.\n    # But to make the first fit, perhaps the priority is 1 for the first can_fit bin, and 0 for others.\n    # However, in vectorized code, it's hard to do that without loops.\n    # So, perhaps for the purpose of this exercise, we can set all can_fit to 1, others to 0.\n    # But that's not truly first fit. Maybe another approach is needed.\n    # Alternatively, use the index of the first can_fit bin.\n    # But that's complicated in vectorized code.\n    # For simplicity, let's proceed with setting can_fit to 1, others to 0.\n    return priority\n\nHeuristic 4: Largest Bin\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    can_fit = bins >= item\n    priority = np.zeros_like(bins)\n    priority[can_fit] = bins[can_fit]\n    return priority\n\nHeuristic 5: Smallest Bin\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    can_fit = bins >= item\n    priority = np.zeros_like(bins)\n    priority[can_fit] = bins[can_fit]\n    # To prioritize the smallest bin, we can take the reciprocal of bin size.\n    # So, smaller bins have higher priority.\n    priority[can_fit] = 1 / bins[can_fit]\n    return priority\n\nHeuristic 6: Minimal Waste\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarra